    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1975-04-11T19:45:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1975-04-11T19:45:00-05:00" n="228"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d228">
                <head>228. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Cambodia</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d228fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_FGR1"
                            >Ford</persName> Library, National Security Adviser, Presidential
                        Country Files for East Asia and the Pacific, Box 4, Cambodia, State
                        Department Telegrams, To <gloss target="#t_SecState1">SECSTATE</gloss>,
                            <gloss target="#t_Nodis1">Nodis</gloss> (6). Secret; <gloss
                            target="#t_Nodis1">Nodis</gloss>; Flash. Repeated to Beijing.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Phnom Penh</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1975-04-12T00:45:00+00:00">April 12, 1975,
                        0045Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6134. For the Secretary from Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DJG1"
                        >Dean</persName>. Subject: Continuing Contacts with <gloss target="#t_GKR1"
                        >GKR</gloss>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Saw <persName corresp="#p_SK1">Saukham Khoy</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_LB1">Long Boret</persName> between 7:00 and 7:30 morning
                        April 12. I conveyed thrust of State 83356<note n="2" xml:id="d228fn2"
                            >Telegram 83356 to Phnom Penh, April 11, contained information on the
                            U.S. offer to evacuate certain Cambodian officials. (National Archives,
                                <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, State Archiving System)</note>
                        to <persName corresp="#p_SK1">Saukham Khoy</persName>. He thought mostly
                        women and children of Khmer VIPs would take advantage of our offer to depart
                        with us this morning. He had not yet made up his mind whether to stay or
                        leave.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Above all, I told him I am going to Bangkok and will remain in Bangkok and
                        I would find ways to stay in touch with whatever elements of the <gloss
                            target="#t_GKR1">GKR</gloss> remain behind. I made similar pitch with
                            <persName corresp="#p_LB1">Long Boret</persName>.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Also mentioned to both of them that President’s message to Congress<note
                            n="3" xml:id="d228fn3">See <ref target="#d217">Document
                            217</ref>.</note> did not repeat not imply we were abandoning our
                        efforts to obtain additional assistance from Congress for Khmer
                        Republic.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>Dean</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
